SIMPLE: hardy
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hardy
<hw>Har"dy</hw> <pr>(h⟦aum⟧r"d⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Hardier</adjf>
<pr>(-d⟦icr⟧*⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Hardiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[F. <ets>hardi</ets>, p. p. fr.
OF. <ets>hardir</ets> to make bold; of German origin, cf. OHG.
<ets>hertan</ets> to harden, G. <ets>h⟦aum⟧rten</ets>. See
<er>Hard</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Bold; brave; stout;
daring; resolute; intrepid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hap helpeth <qex>hardy</qex> man alway.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Confident; full of assurance; in a bad sense,
morally hardened; shameless.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Strong; firm; compact.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[A] blast may shake in pieces his <qex>hardy</qex> fabric.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Inured to fatigue or hardships; strong; capable of
endurance; <as>as, a <ex>hardy</ex> veteran; a <ex>hardy</ex>
mariner.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Able to withstand the cold of winter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Plants which are <xex>hardy</xex> in Virginia may perish
in New England. <xex>Half-hardy</xex> plants are those which are able to
withstand mild winters or moderate frosts.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hardy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hardy
<hw>Har"dy</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A blacksmith's fuller or chisel,
having a square shank for insertion into a square hole in an anvil,
called the <ecol><b>hardy hole</b></ecol>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hare</ent>⟦br⟧
